WEBVTT



00:00:08.768 --> 00:00:18.816
This week we're getting ever closer to Jerusalem and I'm glad you've joined us for our walk with Jesus. I'm going to start in Matthew 20. It's a rather short

00:00:18.336 --> 00:00:21.184
2 Peter 4, verse 29.

00:00:21.152 --> 00:00:27.840
It says this, "As Jesus and his disciples were leaving Jericho, a large crowd followed.

00:00:27.872 --> 00:00:37.632
Two blind men were sitting on the roadside, and when they heard that Jesus was going by, they shouted, "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us!"

00:00:37.408 --> 00:00:40.960
The crowd reviewed them and told them to be quiet.

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:46.656
But they shouted all the louder, "Lord, Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us."

00:00:46.752 --> 00:00:49.504
Jesus stopped and called to them.

00:00:49.344 --> 00:00:52.544
"What do you want me to do for you?" he asked.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:55.712
Lord, they answered, "We want our sights."

00:00:55.712 --> 00:01:00.320
Jesus had compassion on them and touched their eyes.

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:03.200
Immediately they receive their site.

00:01:02.976 --> 00:01:04.736
And followed him.

00:01:05.344 --> 00:01:07.776
Can you imagine the setting?

00:01:07.584 --> 00:01:11.744
These men, the incredible joy of this

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:16.736
Darkness turning to light, this blindness turning to sight.

00:01:16.768 --> 00:01:26.816
When I read this account, I actually thought of the words of John Newton, those famous words, "Amazing Grace, how sweet the sound that saved a wretch like me."

00:01:26.336 --> 00:01:32.640
I once was lost, but now I'm found, was blind, but now I see.

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:37.632
I know these men didn't know those words, but I can imagine their joy was similar.

00:01:37.664 --> 00:01:47.712
John Newton had an incredible testimony as well. He was a British sea captain, a slave trader, who literally came to know Jesus.

00:01:47.232 --> 00:01:54.880
Jesus, and God transformed him through the power of Christ. He came out of darkness and into this glorious place.

00:01:54.624 --> 00:01:55.840
Light

00:01:55.968 --> 00:02:05.120
I love how this imagery is all through the Bible. We see words and imagery that talks about the darkness of sin.

00:02:05.056 --> 00:02:07.648
And then being brought into the light

00:02:07.488 --> 00:02:10.656
The idea of literally being blind,

00:02:10.496 --> 00:02:13.760
But then having receiving sites

00:02:14.144 --> 00:02:24.192
In our Bible study this year, we're in Acts in the Bible, and it's the story of the early church. And I love this book because they're so much more

00:02:23.712 --> 00:02:29.536
Old mud, darkness turning to light, blindness turning to sight, and

00:02:29.056 --> 00:02:37.248
One of the main characters is a man named Paul. He was known as Saul early in the book, but Paul was one of the greatest

00:02:37.184 --> 00:02:46.464
persecutors of the church. He literally would go town to town to arrest and throw into prison those who followed Jesus.

00:02:46.368 --> 00:02:48.064
He was zealous.

00:02:47.968 --> 00:02:58.016
And yet one day he was on the road to Damascus to do that very thing to the believers. When the Lord Jesus shone before him and

00:02:57.536 --> 00:02:59.488
Him in all his glory.

00:02:59.072 --> 00:03:03.808
And Paul was literally cast to the ground blind.

00:03:03.584 --> 00:03:13.632
Somebody led him into the city and for three days he sat there blind really at an outward manifestation of the inner real inward reality

00:03:13.152 --> 00:03:16.192
word reality of his blindness.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:21.024
Well, one day God sent Ananias, a disciple,

00:03:20.768 --> 00:03:30.816
And Ananias came in, he prayed over Paul, and it says in the scripture that literally there was something like scales that fell from his eyes, and all of a sudden he saw. It was the

00:03:30.336 --> 00:03:40.384
It was three days after he became blind that he was brought into the light, very similar to what we read about the resurrection. But he came to faith and he

00:03:39.904 --> 00:03:48.128
And his eyes were opened. He was given a new commission, a new calling. In fact, Jesus said to him in Acts 26, 14 through 15, he said,

00:03:48.384 --> 00:03:51.232
He said, "I'm sending you to the nations."

00:03:50.816 --> 00:03:53.504
To open spiritual eyes

00:03:53.312 --> 00:03:59.296
so that they may turn from darkness to light, from the power of Satan to God.

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:05.440
Well this is what God loves to do. He loves to bring people out of darkness.

00:04:05.216 --> 00:04:07.520
Into the light of his presence

00:04:07.392 --> 00:04:10.016
He loves to bring spiritual sight.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:11.648
To those who are blind.

00:04:11.872 --> 00:04:14.176
But my question today is this:

00:04:14.144 --> 00:04:17.792
Do you remember when you first saw the lights?

00:04:17.664 --> 00:04:22.784
When your eyes were opened to God's incredible gift through Christ,

00:04:22.848 --> 00:04:28.320
When you were brought into the light of understanding that God loved you and cared for you,

00:04:28.544 --> 00:04:33.920
Well, the season of Lent is an opportunity to remember what God has done.

00:04:34.176 --> 00:04:38.592
To ask him to restore the joy of our salvation.

00:04:38.688 --> 00:04:42.208
To reflect on the fact that we once were blind,

00:04:41.952 --> 00:04:48.192
But now we see all because of what Jesus did for you and for me.
